Im a big supporter of the RTA rules.  I also support teamwork in situations where the content is not contested.  On many occasions guilds have teamed up to go kill in chardok for cleric epics, a crucial step in a guilds ability to advance in the game.  Now im not going to go back to archived post to see if a big deal was made when guilds started doing this, but I suspect it was not a big deal then, and it should not be now.<br>
<br>
I see AD/Grummus/Behemoth to be very similar types of encounters to chardok because <br>
<br>
1) They are neccessary in a guilds capacity to progress through the game.<br>
2) No rotation is needed since this content is not contested.<br>
<br>
Does this mean that the guilds who team up now will 'team' up agains the mobs down the road to further their progression?  The difference is that the content further down the line will probably be contested, especially as more guilds make it to that far.  So in the interest of fairness, the smaller guilds would have to respect the rules of the RTA.  They've respected them up till now, why change later?  Now smaller guilds may choose to team up on PoP mobs on rotation down the road, but would do so at the cost of forming an alliance and sharing all rotation content as a single entity.  That would be there right.  Lets make sure that the mobs on rotation deserve to be on rotation and not have all guilds on auto-pass.<br>
<br>
We understand that larger guilds wont break up into smaller pieces to get greater access to weaker rotation content, and the smaller guilds will respect that content on rotation need to be engaged in manner outlined by the regulations put forth by the RTA.  <br>
<br>
But to raise such alarm at a team kill on AD is a bit ridiculous.  Over-reactionalism at its best.<br>
